   "source": [
    "# LLM-as-Judge: Classroom Experiment\n",
    "### Agent Evals for Digital Humanities\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "In this exercise you will:\n",
    "1. Look at outputs from an agent that summarises 19th-century letters\n",
    "2. Write your own **judge criteria** in plain English\n",
    "3. Run MLflow's LLM judge against the dataset\n",
    "4. Compare your results with the rest of the class\n",
    "\n",
    "**Key question to keep in mind:** Does the judge agree with *you*? And does it agree with your classmates?\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Cell 1 — Install dependencies\n",
    "Run this first. The kernel will restart automatically — that is expected."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%pip install --upgrade \"mlflow[databricks]>=3.4.0\" --quiet\n",
    "dbutils.library.restartPython()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Cell 2 — Imports"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import mlflow\n",
    "from mlflow.genai.scorers import Guidelines\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"MLflow version: {mlflow.__version__}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Cell 3 — Set up your MLflow experiment\n",
    "\n",
    "Change `YOUR_NAME` so your results are identifiable when we compare as a class."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "YOUR_NAME = \"student_1\"  # <-- change this!\n",
    "\n",
    "mlflow.set_experiment(f\"/Shared/llm_judge_experiment_{YOUR_NAME}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Experiment set for: {YOUR_NAME}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Cell 4 — The dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "Each row contains:\n",
    "- `inputs`: the task given to the agent\n",
    "- `outputs`: the agent's response\n",
    "- `quality`: a label for *your* reference (the judge doesn't see this)\n",
    "- `notes`: hints about what is wrong or right\n",
    "\n",
    "Read through all 8 examples before writing your judge criteria."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "eval_data = [\n",
    "    # ---- GOOD outputs ----\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        \"inputs\": {\n",
    "            \"task\": \"Summarise this 1847 letter from a mill worker in Leeds to her sister, preserving emotional tone.\",\n",
    "            \"source_text\": \"My dearest Eliza, I write to you in great distress. The foreman has reduced our wages again this fortnight and I fear we shall not make the rent. Little Thomas coughs through the night and I dare not fetch the physician for cost. I remain, your loving sister, Mary.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"outputs\": {\n",
    "            \"response\": \"Mary writes to her sister Eliza in 1847 with deep anxiety about her family's finances. The mill foreman has cut wages for the second time in a fortnight, threatening their ability to pay rent. She is also worried about her son Thomas, who has a persistent night cough, but cannot afford a doctor. The letter conveys exhaustion and fear, closing with characteristic Victorian affection.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"quality\": \"good\",\n",
    "        \"notes\": \"Accurate, preserves tone, no anachronism, no hallucination.\"\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        \"inputs\": {\n",
    "            \"task\": \"Summarise this 1883 letter from a clergyman in rural Devon to the Bishop of Exeter.\",\n",
    "            \"source_text\": \"My Lord Bishop, I humbly petition your Lordship's attention to the matter of the parish school. The roof has been in grievous disrepair these three winters past and the children suffer damp and cold. I have applied twice to the vestry and received no satisfaction. Your Lordship's intercession would be greatly valued by your obedient servant, Rev. H. Stokes.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"outputs\": {\n",
    "            \"response\": \"Reverend Stokes writes to the Bishop of Exeter in 1883 to request his intervention regarding the parish school's deteriorating roof, which has been unrepaired for three winters. Two appeals to the vestry have been unsuccessful. The letter is formal and deferential in register, consistent with Victorian clerical correspondence.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"quality\": \"good\",\n",
    "        \"notes\": \"Accurate summary, correct register noted, no anachronism.\"\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        \"inputs\": {\n",
    "            \"task\": \"Summarise this 1851 letter from an Irish emigrant in New York to his family in County Clare.\",\n",
    "            \"source_text\": \"Dear Father and Mother, I arrived safe to New York after seven weeks at sea. The crossing was terrible hard. I have found lodging with Brennan's cousin on Mulberry Street and have work at the docks three days this week. I send five shillings. God willing I shall send more at Christmas. Your devoted son, Patrick.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"outputs\": {\n",
    "            \"response\": \"Patrick writes home to County Clare in 1851 to reassure his parents of his safe arrival in New York after a gruelling seven-week Atlantic crossing. He has found lodging through a family connection and begun work at the docks. He encloses five shillings and promises more at Christmas. The tone is dutiful and quietly optimistic despite evident hardship.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"quality\": \"good\",\n",
    "        \"notes\": \"Accurate, preserves emotional nuance (dutiful optimism), no invented detail.\"\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    # ---- BAD outputs: anachronism ----\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        \"inputs\": {\n",
    "            \"task\": \"Summarise this 1847 letter from a mill worker in Leeds to her sister, preserving emotional tone.\",\n",
    "            \"source_text\": \"My dearest Eliza, I write to you in great distress. The foreman has reduced our wages again this fortnight and I fear we shall not make the rent. Little Thomas coughs through the night and I dare not fetch the physician for cost. I remain, your loving sister, Mary.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"outputs\": {\n",
    "            \"response\": \"In this text, Mary is basically stressed about money and worried her kid is sick. The boss cut her pay again which is super frustrating. She can't afford healthcare which is a major issue. It's giving real poverty-trap energy.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"quality\": \"bad\",\n",
    "        \"notes\": \"Severe anachronism: 'basically', 'super frustrating', 'major issue', 'giving real ... energy'. Tone is completely wrong.\"\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        \"inputs\": {\n",
    "            \"task\": \"Summarise this 1883 letter from a clergyman in rural Devon to the Bishop of Exeter.\",\n",
    "            \"source_text\": \"My Lord Bishop, I humbly petition your Lordship's attention to the matter of the parish school. The roof has been in grievous disrepair these three winters past and the children suffer damp and cold. I have applied twice to the vestry and received no satisfaction. Your Lordship's intercession would be greatly valued by your obedient servant, Rev. H. Stokes.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"outputs\": {\n",
    "            \"response\": \"Rev Stokes is basically asking his boss to step in because the school building has been a mess for ages. He's already tried twice to escalate internally but got nowhere. He's hoping leadership will do something about it.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"quality\": \"bad\",\n",
    "        \"notes\": \"Anachronistic corporate language: 'escalate internally', 'leadership', 'boss'. Completely flattens the Victorian ecclesiastical register.\"\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    # ---- BAD outputs: hallucination ----\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        \"inputs\": {\n",
    "            \"task\": \"Summarise this 1851 letter from an Irish emigrant in New York to his family in County Clare.\",\n",
    "            \"source_text\": \"Dear Father and Mother, I arrived safe to New York after seven weeks at sea. The crossing was terrible hard. I have found lodging with Brennan's cousin on Mulberry Street and have work at the docks three days this week. I send five shillings. God willing I shall send more at Christmas. Your devoted son, Patrick.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"outputs\": {\n",
    "            \"response\": \"Patrick arrived safely in New York after seven weeks at sea. He has found work in a factory and is earning a steady wage. He mentions his wife and three children have also made the crossing safely. He sends money home and plans to visit Ireland next spring.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"quality\": \"bad\",\n",
    "        \"notes\": \"Multiple hallucinations: 'factory' (letter says docks), 'wife and three children' (not mentioned), 'plans to visit Ireland' (not in source).\"\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    # ---- BORDERLINE outputs ----\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        \"inputs\": {\n",
    "            \"task\": \"Summarise this 1847 letter from a mill worker in Leeds to her sister, preserving emotional tone.\",\n",
    "            \"source_text\": \"My dearest Eliza, I write to you in great distress. The foreman has reduced our wages again this fortnight and I fear we shall not make the rent. Little Thomas coughs through the night and I dare not fetch the physician for cost. I remain, your loving sister, Mary.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"outputs\": {\n",
    "            \"response\": \"Mary writes to her sister Eliza in 1847 about financial difficulties. Her wages have been cut and she is concerned about paying rent. Her son Thomas is ill. She cannot afford a doctor. The letter ends affectionately.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"quality\": \"borderline\",\n",
    "        \"notes\": \"Factually accurate but emotionally flat. Strips the urgency and fear from the original. No anachronism but misses the 'preserving emotional tone' instruction.\"\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        \"inputs\": {\n",
    "            \"task\": \"Summarise this 1883 letter from a clergyman in rural Devon to the Bishop of Exeter.\",\n",
    "            \"source_text\": \"My Lord Bishop, I humbly petition your Lordship's attention to the matter of the parish school. The roof has been in grievous disrepair these three winters past and the children suffer damp and cold. I have applied twice to the vestry and received no satisfaction. Your Lordship's intercession would be greatly valued by your obedient servant, Rev. H. Stokes.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"outputs\": {\n",
    "            \"response\": \"In an 1883 letter, Reverend Stokes appeals to the Bishop of Exeter for help with the parish school's long-neglected roof. After two failed attempts to resolve the issue through the vestry, he asks the Bishop to intervene. The letter is polite and respectful.\"\n",
    "        },\n",
    "        \"quality\": \"borderline\",\n",
    "        \"notes\": \"Accurate but 'polite and respectful' undersells the formal Victorian deference of the original. Minor but meaningful loss of register.\"\n",
    "    }\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Preview the dataset\n",
    "df_preview = pd.DataFrame([\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        \"#\": i+1,\n",
    "        \"task (truncated)\": row[\"inputs\"][\"task\"][:60] + \"...\",\n",
    "        \"quality label\": row[\"quality\"],\n",
    "        \"notes\": row[\"notes\"]\n",
    "    }\n",
    "    for i, row in enumerate(eval_data)\n",
    "])\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Dataset contains {len(eval_data)} examples\\n\")\n",
    "display(df_preview)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Cell 5 — ✏️ Write your judge criteria\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the key exercise. Edit the `guidelines` list below.\n",
    "\n",
    "Each item is a **pass/fail rule** written in plain English.  \n",
    "The judge will evaluate every output against every rule.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Tips:**\n",
    "- Be specific — vague rules produce noisy results\n",
    "- Try 2–4 criteria (too many dilutes the signal)\n",
    "- Think about what *kind* of failure you most care about: anachronism? hallucination? missing tone?\n",
    "\n",
    "Some example criteria to get you started (feel free to replace them entirely):\n",
    "```\n",
    "\"The summary must not use slang, idioms, or vocabulary that postdates 1900\"\n",
    "\"The summary must not introduce facts or details not present in the source letter\"\n",
    "\"The summary must reflect the emotional tone described in the task instruction\"\n",
    "\"The summary must use vocabulary and register appropriate to the historical period\"\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# ============================================================\n",
    "# EDIT THIS CELL — write your own judge criteria\n",
    "# ============================================================\n",
    "\n",
    "my_guidelines = [\n",
    "    \"The summary must not use slang, idioms, or vocabulary that postdates 1900\",\n",
    "    \"The summary must not introduce facts or details not present in the source letter\",\n",
    "    \"The summary must reflect the emotional tone described in the task instruction\",\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "# ============================================================\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Your judge criteria:\")\n",
    "for i, g in enumerate(my_guidelines, 1):\n",
    "    print(f\"  {i}. {g}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Cell 6 — Run the judge\n",
    "\n",
    "This sends each output to the Databricks-hosted LLM judge with your criteria.  \n",
    "It takes ~1–2 minutes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "judge = Guidelines(\n",
    "    name=f\"{YOUR_NAME}_judge\",\n",
    "    guidelines=my_guidelines\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Strip the 'quality' and 'notes' keys — the judge should not see them\n",
    "judge_data = [\n",
    "    {\"inputs\": row[\"inputs\"], \"outputs\": row[\"outputs\"]}\n",
    "    for row in eval_data\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Running judge evaluation...\")\n",
    "results = mlflow.genai.evaluate(\n",
    "    data=judge_data,\n",
    "    scorers=[judge]\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\nDone! Results logged to MLflow.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Cell 7 — Inspect results"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Combine judge results with our ground-truth labels for comparison\n",
    "results_df = results.tables[\"eval_results_table\"].copy()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add back our human quality labels\n",
    "results_df[\"human_label\"] = [row[\"quality\"] for row in eval_data]\n",
    "results_df[\"notes\"] = [row[\"notes\"] for row in eval_data]\n",
    "\n",
    "display(results_df)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Cell 8 — Agreement analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "How well does the LLM judge align with our human labels?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "score_col = [c for c in results_df.columns if YOUR_NAME in c and \"score\" in c.lower()]\n",
    "\n",
    "if score_col:\n",
    "    col = score_col[0]\n",
    "    results_df[\"judge_pass\"] = results_df[col].apply(lambda x: \"pass\" if x == 1.0 else \"fail\")\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Simple agreement: did the judge pass good outputs and fail bad ones?\n",
    "    results_df[\"human_binary\"] = results_df[\"human_label\"].apply(\n",
    "        lambda x: \"pass\" if x == \"good\" else (\"borderline\" if x == \"borderline\" else \"fail\")\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    \n",
    "    clear_cases = results_df[results_df[\"human_binary\"] != \"borderline\"]\n",
    "    agreement = (clear_cases[\"judge_pass\"] == clear_cases[\"human_binary\"]).mean()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    print(f\"Judge agreement with human labels (excluding borderline): {agreement:.0%}\")\n",
    "    print()\n",
    "    print(\"Row-by-row breakdown:\")\n",
    "    display(results_df[[\"human_label\", \"judge_pass\", \"notes\"]])\nelse:\n",
    "    print(\"Could not find score column — check the column names above and adjust manually.\")\n",
    "    print(\"Available columns:\", list(results_df.columns))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Cell 9 — 🔁 Vary the judge prompt\n",
    "\n",
    "Now re-run with a **different** framing of the same criteria.  \n",
    "For example, change:\n",
    "\n",
    "> `\"The summary must not use vocabulary that postdates 1900\"`\n",
    "\n",
    "to:\n",
    "\n",
    "> `\"The language in the summary should feel consistent with the historical period of the letter\"`\n",
    "\n",
    "How sensitive is the judge to how you phrase the rule?\n",
    "\n",
    "Record both pass rates in the table below for class discussion."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# ============================================================\n",
    "# EDIT THIS CELL — rephrased version of your criteria\n",
    "# ============================================================\n",
    "\n",
    "my_guidelines_v2 = [\n",
    "    \"The language in the summary should feel consistent with the historical period of the letter\",\n",
    "    \"The summary should only contain information that appears in the source text\",\n",
    "    \"The emotional character of the original letter should come through in the summary\",\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "# ============================================================\n",
    "\n",
    "judge_v2 = Guidelines(\n",
    "    name=f\"{YOUR_NAME}_judge_v2\",\n",
    "    guidelines=my_guidelines_v2\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "results_v2 = mlflow.genai.evaluate(\n",
    "    data=judge_data,\n",
    "    scorers=[judge_v2]\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"v2 results:\")\n",
    "display(results_v2.tables[\"eval_results_table\"])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Cell 10 — Class discussion prompts\n",
    "\n",
    "Use this cell to take notes during the debrief.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Questions to explore:**\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Which outputs did your judge **mis-classify**? Why do you think it got them wrong?\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Did rephrasing your criteria in Cell 9 change the results? On which rows?\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Look at the **borderline cases** (rows 7 and 8). Did your judge pass or fail them?  \n",
    "   Do you agree with the judge's decision?\n",
    "\n",
    "4. What does this tell you about the difference between *knowing* what a good summary looks like  \n",
    "   and *specifying* it well enough for an automated judge?\n",
    "\n",
    "5. If you were building a real DH eval pipeline, what would you add to improve the judge?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Notes cell — jot anything down here as plain comments or strings\n",
    "\n",
    "notes = \"\"\"\n",
    "My judge got these rows wrong: \n",
    "Rephrasing changed results on rows: \n",
    "Borderline cases — my judge said: \n",
    "Biggest insight: \n",
    "\"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "print(notes)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Fallback: heuristic judge (no LLM required)\n",
    "\n",
    "If the Databricks-hosted judge is unavailable, run this cell instead.  \n",
    "It uses simple keyword matching to flag anachronisms — a useful contrast with the LLM judge."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "ANACHRONISTIC_TERMS = [\n",
    "    \"basically\", \"super\", \"frustrating\", \"major issue\", \"energy\",\n",
    "    \"stress\", \"stressed\", \"escalate\", \"leadership\", \"boss\",\n",
    "    \"healthcare\", \"okay\", \"ok\", \"guy\", \"guys\", \"stuff\",\n",
    "    \"vibe\", \"vibes\", \"literally\", \"honestly\", \"toxic\"\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "def heuristic_judge(response_text):\n",
    "    text_lower = response_text.lower()\n",
    "    flagged = [term for term in ANACHRONISTIC_TERMS if term in text_lower]\n",
    "    return {\n",
    "        \"pass\": len(flagged) == 0,\n",
    "        \"flagged_terms\": flagged\n",
    "    }\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Heuristic judge results:\\n\")\n",
    "for i, row in enumerate(eval_data):\n",
    "    result = heuristic_judge(row[\"outputs\"][\"response\"])\n",
    "    status = \"✅ PASS\" if result[\"pass\"] else \"❌ FAIL\"\n",
    "    flagged = f\" — flagged: {result['flagged_terms']}\" if result[\"flagged_terms\"] else \"\"\n",
    "    print(f\"Row {i+1} [{row['quality']:>10}]  {status}{flagged}\")"
   ]
  }
 ]
}"
